  "slug": "roast-venison-haunch",
  "title": "Roast Venison Haunch",
  "subtitle": "A rich, lean joint marinated overnight and roasted to a deep red-pink centre",
  "excerpt": "Venison haunch is the back leg, sold bone-in or boned and rolled. It is the leanest of all red meat roasting joints and dries quickly if overcooked. A wine and juniper marinade overnight adds moisture and flavour; roast to 58-60°C for red-pink.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Jane Grigson, English Food (1974): venison haunch with red wine and juniper. Traditional British estate cookery. Hugh Fearnley-Whittingstall, The River Cottage Meat Book (2004): modern venison roasting guidance.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Venison haunch roasts like topside beef: lean, needing a thermometer rather than time alone, and unforgiving above 65°C. The difference is in the flavour; venison has a depth and iron richness that benefits from a wine and juniper ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "marinade",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr3kft0000lsv4ey83rfqh"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " overnight. The marinade also provides the base for the sauce.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pull the joint at 58-60°C for a deeply red-pink interior. Venison served at medium-well is dry and disappointing. ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "Juniper berries",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr3kgh0001lsv4z0c1rrvw"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " are the defining spice here; lightly crush them in a pestle before adding to the marinade to release the volatile oils.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
