      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Marinate overnight",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{red-wine}} of red wine",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{olive-oil}} of olive oil",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", garlic, crushed ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{juniper-berries}} juniper berries",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", thyme, and bay leaves in a large non-reactive dish. Add the venison, turn to coat, cover, and refrigerate for at least 12 hours, turning once.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Roast to temperature",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Remove the joint from the marinade 1 hour before cooking; reserve the marinade. Pat the meat dry. Rub with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Lay bacon rashers over the joint if using. Heat the oven to 220°C (200°C fan) and roast for 20 minutes to colour the surface. Reduce to 180°C (160°C fan) and continue until the centre reads 58-60°C for red-pink, or 62°C for medium-pink. Begin probing after 40 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rest and make the sauce",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Transfer to a warm board and rest for 20 minutes. In the roasting pan, pour in the strained marinade and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-beef}} of beef stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Scrape the fond and reduce by half over high heat. Stir in ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{jam}} of redcurrant jelly",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and season. Strain into a warm jug. Carve the joint in thin slices across the grain.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Probe from the start of checking and pull immediately at 60°C. Bard lean joints with bacon or lard the flesh with thin strips of bacon fat.",
              "cause": "Overcooked past 70°C, or joint was too lean without barding",
              "symptom": "Meat is dry and brown throughout"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Strain the marinade before adding to the pan and simmer gently for 5 minutes before adding stock. Redcurrant jelly balances bitterness.",
              "cause": "Marinade reduced too quickly and the alcohol became harsh",
              "symptom": "Sauce is bitter"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Marinade overnight masks this to some degree. Farmed venison is consistently mild; source from a reputable game dealer or farm shop.",
              "cause": "Wild venison with a strong gamy character, or improperly hung",
              "symptom": "The meat smells very strong"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Ask the butcher to tie the joint to an even cylinder. Alternatively use the probe to track the thickest section.",
              "cause": "Boned and rolled joint was not tied evenly, creating thick and thin sections",
              "symptom": "Joint is unevenly cooked"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Venison has been a British estate table meat for centuries, reserved historically for the landowner's table. It is now widely available through farm shops, specialist butchers, and supermarkets. The flavour is denser and more mineral than beef, well-paired with the sharp sweetness of redcurrant jelly and the piney note of juniper. Serve with celeriac mash or roast root vegetables.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
